'''Air stagnation''' is a phenomenon which occurs when an [[air mass]] remains over an area for an extended period. Stagnation events strongly correlates with poor air quality. <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leung|first1=L. Ruby|last2=Gustafson Jr|first2=William I.|title=Potential regional climate change and implications to U.S. air quality|journal=Geophysical Research Letters|date=Aug 26, 2005|volume=32|issue=16|doi=10.1029/2005GL022911|bibcode=2005GeoRL..3216711L}}</ref> Due to light winds and lack of [[precipitation (meteorology)|precipitation]], [[pollutant]]s cannot be cleared from the air, either [[gas]]eous (like [[ozone]]) or [[particulate]] (like [[soot]] or dust). Subsidence produced directly under the [[subtropical ridge]] can lead to a buildup of particulates in urban areas under the ridge, leading to widespread [[haze]].<ref>Myanmar government (2007). [http://www.kjc.gov.my/english/education/weather/haze01.html Haze.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080224035453/http://www.kjc.gov.my/english/education/weather/haze01.html |date=2008-02-24 }} Retrieved on 2007-02-11.</ref> If the low level [[relative humidity]] rises towards 100 percent overnight, [[fog]] can form.<ref>Robert Tardif (2002). [http://www.rap.ucar.edu/staff/tardif/Documents/CUprojects/ATOC5600/fog_characteristics.htm Fog characteristics.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520021633/http://www.rap.ucar.edu/staff/tardif/Documents/CUprojects/ATOC5600/fog_characteristics.htm |date=2011-05-20 }} [[University Corporation for Atmospheric Research]]. Retrieved on 2007-02-11.</ref> In the [[United States]], the [[National Weather Service]] issues an ''Air Stagnation Advisory'' when these conditions are likely to occur.<ref>[[National Weather Service]] glossary. [http://www.nws.noaa.gov/glossary/index.php?word=air+stagnation Air Stagnation.] Retrieved on 2008-05-31.</ref>
In the U.S., the numbers of stagnation days during winter and spring tend to be much smaller than those during summer and fall.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leung|first1=L. Ruby|last2=Gustafson Jr|first2=William I.|title=Potential regional climate change and implications to U.S. air quality|journal=Geophysical Research Letters|date=Aug 26, 2005|volume=32|issue=16|doi=10.1029/2005GL022911|bibcode=2005GeoRL..3216711L}}</ref> Spatial variations during winter and spring tend to be incoherent as well.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leung|first1=L. Ruby|last2=Gustafson Jr|first2=William I.|title=Potential regional climate change and implications to U.S. air quality|journal=Geophysical Research Letters|date=Aug 26, 2005|volume=32|issue=16|doi=10.1029/2005GL022911|bibcode=2005GeoRL..3216711L}}</ref>
