{{Infobox institute |name = GlamSci |image = File:GlamSci logo with moto.jpeg |image_name = |image_size = |image_alt = |caption = GlamSci logo |latin_name = |motto = |founder = Amy King |established = 2013 |mission = women and minorities in STEM education and training |focus = |president = |chairman = |head_label = |head = |faculty = |adjunct_faculty = |staff = |key_people = |budget = £2,100 non-profit<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://beta.charitycommission.gov.uk/charity-details/?regid=1168900&subid=0|title=Charity Details|website=beta.charitycommission.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-08-29}}</ref> |endowment = |debt = |num_members = |subsidiaries = |owner = |non-profit_slogan = |former_name = |location = |city = |state = |province = |country = [[Great Britain]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reportingaccounts.com/uk/CE008626/glamsci/|title=Company Glamsci CE008626 brought to you free by Reporting Accounts|website=www.reportingaccounts.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-29}}</ref> |coor = |address = |website = www.GlamSci.org |dissolved = |footnotes = }}
'''GlamSci''' is a British non-profit which focuses on helping [[Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics|STEM]] education and training to be more relatable to the general public.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/vivian-chan/4-stories-that-show-scien_b_18171712.html?guccounter=1&guce_referrer_us=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS91cmw_&guce_referrer_cs=zqMJbkEZxOHaLOAC7MSKWA|title=Four Stories That Show Science Still Has A Gender Problem|date=2017-10-09|work=HuffPost UK|access-date=2018-10-01|language=en-GB}}</ref>
==Activities== GlamSci provides educational support to promote STEM fields<ref name=":0" /> for disadvantaged groups and minorities around the UK and internationally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.festivaloflearning.org.uk/2017/06/adult-learning-helped-change-lives-others/|title=Adult learning helped me change the lives of others {{!}} Festival of Learning|last=|first=|date=|website=Festival of Learning|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://governmentscienceandengineering.blog.gov.uk/2016/11/04/gse-opportunities-a-blogging-opportunity-food-standards-agency-vacancies-and-more/|title=GSE Opportunities: A blogging opportunity, Food Standards Agency vacancies and more. - Government Science and Engineering|website=governmentscienceandengineering.blog.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-10-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sciencelive.net/user/604/|title=Science Live - GlamSci|last=Scott|first=Ben|website=www.sciencelive.net|language=en|access-date=2018-10-01}}</ref> This is done by providing a variety of events and training for schools, colleges and community centres and youth groups, including workshops, motivational talks, mentoring, English and Maths skills training, work placements and CV, UCAS and careers advice<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bvsc.co.uk/contacts/view/14048|title=Bexley Voluntary Service Council|website=www.bvsc.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-10-01}}</ref>. GlamSci also provides general interest events to encourage members of the public to get 'hands-on' with STEM;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sunninghillprep.co.uk/sunninghill-girls-flourish-at-land-rover-bar-racing-stem-day/|title=Sunninghill Girls Flourish at Land Rover BAR Racing STEM Day - Sunninghill Prep School|date=2018-04-23|work=Sunninghill Prep School|access-date=2018-10-01|language=en-GB}}</ref> these events include festivals, STEM clubs, and themed days.<ref name=":1" />
==History== ===Origin (2013-2016)===
GlamSci originally started as a blog for the Royal Society of Chemistry (RSC)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencefestival.co.uk/reading-survey-response-amy-king|title=reading experiment survey response - amy king - Edinburgh International Science Festival - Edinburgh International Science Festival|website=Edinburgh International Science Festival|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-10-01}}</ref> known as 'The Life and Times of a Chemistry Nerd', it documented the experiences of GlamSci Co-Founder Amy King through College and University as a young disabled woman in STEM after being "[[Women in STEM fields|repeatedly told "pure science isn’t for girls]]".<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.unialliance.ac.uk/2018/06/06/amy-king-bsc-hons-natural-sciences/|title=Amy King, BSc (Hons) Natural Sciences {{!}} University Alliance|website=www.unialliance.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-08-29}}
GlamSci was unofficially founded in 2013, following a number of requests for female speakers, and workshops from the founding members of GlamSci. </ref> Members have attended "educational events for educators and educational leaders, such as WorldTeachIn, and Athena Swan and Bett events".<ref name=":1" /> GlamSci founding members worked for 3 years offering speakers for these types of educational events and built up a portfolio of other events<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.1851trust.org.uk/1851-trusts-next-generation-roadshow-inspires-girls-science-technology/|title=1851 Trust’s #Next Generation Roadshow inspires girls in Science and Technology - 1851 Trust|date=2017-11-17|work=1851 Trust|access-date=2018-10-01|language=en-GB}}</ref> and support that turned into official GlamSci Events and events.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techtalentcharter.co.uk/another-look-techs-diversity-problem/|title=Another look at tech’s diversity problem - Tech Talent Charter|website=techtalentcharter.co.uk|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-01}}</ref>
===Growth (2016-Present)=== On November 2, 2017, the UK Department of Education recognized Amy King of GlamSci for "inspiring young people to work in science".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/twitter/educationgovuk?year_from=2012&year_to=2017&amount=30&sort=desc&from=990|title=The National Archives - Department for Education {{!}} Twitter Archive - UK Government Web Archive|last=Archives|first=The National|website=webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-10-01}}</ref>
{{as of| 2018}}, it is led by Amy King<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.learningandwork.org.uk/Exhibitor/amy-king/|title=Amy King {{!}} Learning & Work|website=www.learningandwork.org.uk|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-29}}</ref> , who was London’s Adult Learner of the Year in 2014.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsc.org/diversity/175-faces/all-faces/amy-king/|title=Amy King {{!}} 175 Faces of Chemistry|website=www.rsc.org|language=en|access-date=2018-08-29}}</ref> King is joined by fellow Trustees Nicola King, Andrew Church, and Tracy Dyball. GlamSci has support from over 20 volunteer scientists, such as Dr. Julia Attias''','''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.innovaspace.org/blog/category/steam-education|title=Category: STEAM Education|website=InnovaSpace|language=en|access-date=2018-10-01}}</ref> across the country and is working with many organisations to recruit more scientists and expand events.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kentandmedwaystem.org.uk/index.php/events/stem-event-info/776/|title=Space Extravaganza at Wellesley House School|website=www.kentandmedwaystem.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-10-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mkinnovates.co.uk/index.php/participating-organisations|title=Organisations|website=MKInnovates|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-10-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lsec.ac.uk/news/1085-amy-and-the-appliance-of-science|title=Amy and the appliance of science|last=T-Dog|website=LSEC|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-10-01}}</ref> GlamSci prides it's good relationships with volunteers; offering volunteers the same access to GlamSci services as it's users.
