:''For the Australian tennis player, also known as Jack Hawkes, see [[John Hawkes (tennis)]].''
'''John Gregory "Jack" Hawkes''' [[OBE]] [[Fellow of the Linnean Society|FLS]] (27 June 1915 in [[Bristol]] – 6 September 2007 in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]]) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[botanist]], Mason Professor of Botany at the [[University of Birmingham]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Crop Wild Relative Conservation and Use|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MpWeaVxp9gsC&pg=PR18|year=2008|publisher=CABI|isbn=978-1-84593-307-4|pages=18–20|chapter=Jack Hawkes: Plant Collector, Researcher, Mentor and Visionary}}</ref><ref name="Goldman2013">{{cite book|author=Lawrence Goldman|title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography 2005-2008|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nbGcAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA500|date=7 March 2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-967154-0|pages=499–500|chapter=Hawkes, John Gregory}}</ref>

He specialised in studying the taxonomy of wild potato species (''[[Solanum]]'' sect. ''[[Petota]]''), identified sources of resistance to the [[potato cyst nematode]] and played a role in establishing programs to maintain [[agricultural biodiversity]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/professor-jack-hawkes-397143.html |title=Professor Jack Hawkes |publisher=The Independent |date=2007-10-18 |accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1563695/Professor-Jack-Hawkes.html |title=Professor Jack Hawkes |publisher=The Daily Telegraph |date=2007-09-21 |accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref>

He was awarded the [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire|OBE]] in the [[1994 Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |date=10 June 1994 |supp=y |issue=53696 |page=12}}</ref>

