{{for|the Mennonite bishop|Joseph Wenger (bishop)}} {{Use mdy dates|date=October 2011}} {{Infobox Officeholder | name =Joseph N. Wenger | image =Joseph N. Wenger.jpg | caption = |order1 = 1st |title1 = [[Deputy Director of the Armed Forces Security Agency|Deputy Director of the AFSA]], [[United States Navy|USN]] |term_start1 = November 1950 |term_end1 = April 1951 |president1 = |deputy1 = |predecessor1 = ''position created'' |successor1 = [[Travis Hetherington]] |order2 = 1st |title2 = [[Vice Director of the National Security Agency|Vice Director of the NSA]] | term_start2 = December 1952 | term_end2 = November 1953 | president2 = | deputy2 = | predecessor2 = Travis Hetherington | successor2 = [[John Ackerman (United States Air Force officer)|John Ackerman]] | birth_name=Joseph Numa Wenger | birth_date = {{birth date|1901|06|07}} | birth_place = [[Patterson, Louisiana]], U.S. | death_date = {{dda|1970|9|2|1901|6|1}} | death_place = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S. | nickname = | allegiance = USA | branch = [[Image:Seal of the United States Department of the Navy (alternate).svg|25px]] [[United States Navy]] | serviceyears = | rank = [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear-Admiral]] | unit = | commands = | battles = |resting_place={{nowrap|Arlington National Cemetery}} | awards = | relations = }} '''Joseph Numa Wenger''' (June 7, 1901 – September 2, 1970) was a [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear-Admiral]] of the [[United States Navy]] who served as the first [[Deputy Director of the Armed Forces Security Agency|Deputy Director]] of the [[Armed Forces Security Agency]] (AFSA), and later as the first [[Deputy Director of the National Security Agency|Vice Director]] of the [[National Security Agency]], from December 1952 to November 1953, after the separate divisions of the AFSA merged into the NSA. Wenger was one of the leaders responsible for the development of the NSA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsa.gov/about/cryptologic_heritage/hall_of_honor/2005/wenger.shtml|title=Rear Admiral Joseph N. Wenger, USN (1901–1970) 2005 Inductee|date=January 15, 2009|publisher=National Security Agency|accessdate=January 21, 2009}}</ref> He was a native of Patterson, Louisiana.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nsa.gov/public_info/_files/crypto_almanac_50th/Joseph_N._Wenger.pdf |title=Cryptologic Almanac 50th Anniversary Series |format=PDF |accessdate=2012-03-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111028075301/https://www.nsa.gov/public_info/_files/crypto_almanac_50th/Joseph_N._Wenger.pdf |archivedate=October 28, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>
==Work== Wenger was "one of the architects of centralized [[cryptology]]."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsa.gov/about/cryptologic_heritage/center_crypt_history/publications/koreanwar_sigint_bkg.shtml|title=The Korean War: The SIGINT Background Search What's new?|last=Hatch|first=David A.|author2=Robert Louis Benson|publisher=United States National Security Agency|accessdate=December 21, 2008}}</ref> In February 1942 Navy power struggles led to the ousting of [[Laurance Safford]] from [[OP-20-G]]; with two new sections to be headed by Wenger (Communications: Decryption and Translation) and [[John R. Redman]] (Communications: Combat Intelligence). Safford was removed from current intelligence to a support and research role. <ref> {{cite book | last = Layton | first = Edwin | authorlink = Edwin Layton | title = And I was there: Pearl Harbour and Midway – Breaking the Secrets |publisher = William Morrow | date = 1985 | location = New York | page = | pages = 367,368 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = 0-688-04883-8 }} </ref> Safford was sidelined for the remainder of the war, as ultimately was [[Joseph Rochefort]].
Wenger was integral in starting the AFSA (Armed Forces Security Agency), the predecessor to the [[NSA]]. During World War II he suggested that the Navy spend $2 million "to build 360 of its own four wheel bombes" to break the effective British monopoly on the [[Bombe]].<ref>*{{cite book|last=Budiansky |first=Stephen|year=2000|title=Battle of Wits|series=| location=New York|publisher=The Free Press|accessdate=2012-03-07}}</ref> He died in 1970.<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/49336411]</ref>
